There are a few issues. First take a look at the definitions for ATTRIBUTE and EXTENSION:
```
  ATTRIBUTE ::= CLASS {
      &id             OBJECT IDENTIFIER UNIQUE,
      &Type           OPTIONAL,
      &equality-match MATCHING-RULE OPTIONAL,
      &minCount       INTEGER DEFAULT 1,
      &maxCount       INTEGER OPTIONAL
  } WITH SYNTAX {
      [TYPE &Type]
      [EQUALITY MATCHING RULE &equality-match]
      [COUNTS [MIN &minCount] [MAX &maxCount]]
      IDENTIFIED BY &id
  }
  
  EXTENSION ::= CLASS {
      &id  OBJECT IDENTIFIER UNIQUE,
      &ExtnType,
      &Critical    BOOLEAN DEFAULT {TRUE | FALSE }
  } WITH SYNTAX {
      SYNTAX &ExtnType IDENTIFIED BY &id
      [CRITICALITY &Critical]
  }
 ```
Notice ATTRIBUTE uses TYPE and EXTENSION uses SYNTAX. You are using TYPE for both. So change the definitions of ext-evidence and ext-evidenceCerts to use SYNTAX. Also, remove the unnecessary commas from the definitions. There also is no COUNTS field in EXTENSION. Thus:
```
ext-evidence EXTENSION ::= {
  SYNTAX SEQUENCE OF EvidenceBundle
  IDENTIFIED BY id-aa-evidenceStatement
}

ext-evidenceCerts EXTENSION ::= {
  SYNTAX SEQUENCE OF CertificateChoice
  IDENTIFIED BY id-aa-evidenceChainCerts
}

attr-evidence ATTRIBUTE ::= {
  TYPE SEQUENCE OF EvidenceBundle
  IDENTIFIED BY id-aa-evidenceStatement
}

attr-evidenceCerts ATTRIBUTE ::= {
  TYPE SEQUENCE OF CertificateChoice
  COUNTS MAX 1
  IDENTIFIED BY id-aa-evidenceChainCerts
}
```
I got a compilation error on the Evidence Statement definition and changed it to be this (but wasn't really sure what you were aiming for so this may warrant further investigation):
```
EvidenceStatement ::= SEQUENCE {
   type   EVIDENCE-STATEMENT.&id({EvidenceStatementSet}),
   stmt   EVIDENCE-STATEMENT.&Type({EvidenceStatementSet}{@type})
}
```
I also had to define id-aa and id-pkix in the module. The former because I did not have the referenced module lying around and the latter because id-pkix is not defined in the indicated module. It's actually in PKIX1Explicit-2009, not PKIX-CommonTypes-2009.

Other changes I made to get it to compile:

- used fake values for the OIDs (used 9991, 9992 and 9993 for the three TBDs)
- dropped the symbolic name from the leaf element in the OID definitions, i.e., id-aa-evidenceChainCerts OBJECT IDENTIFIER ::= { id-aa 9993 }

I will send you the module I test compiled successfully.

